  <body>
    <segment id="1" parent="18" relname="concession">
Everything about usability is subjective!</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="7" relname="circumstance"> But when a vast majority of
users can figure out an interface with little or no instruction,</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="18" relname="span"> then
it&apos;s considered intuitive.</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="8" relname="volitional-cause">
Actually, since intuitiveness is so closely tied to learnability,</segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="19" relname="span"> I
think the premise discussed in the Preece text would apply (p16):</segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="15" relname="contrast">
products intended for use by the general population, used everyday or
infrequently, must be easy to learn (intuitive),</segment>
    <segment id="10" parent="15" relname="contrast"> while products that are
complex by design and have much more functionality require more time and
effort to learn.</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="11" relname="antithesis">
We talk about the &apos;intuitiveness&apos; of Word, or some other complex
application,</segment>
    <segment id="11" parent="21" relname="span"> but we weren&apos;t born knowing what a &quot;File Save&quot; or &quot;Paste&quot;
icon means.</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="12" relname="nonvolitional-cause"> These things have evolved to make certain things more
consistent in complex applications</segment>
    <segment id="12" parent="16" relname="span"> and, hence, make other applications
adhering to these principles seem more intuitive.</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="13" relname="condition">
If a free-thinker came up with a better icon for &quot;Save&quot; or &quot;Paste&quot;,</segment>
    <segment id="13" parent="17" relname="span"> then
I feel sure that it would be rejected</segment>
    <segment id="14" parent="13" relname="nonvolitional-cause"> because it is inconsistent with
current established conventions.</segment>
